  "title": "A structural basis for the selection of dominant alphabeta T cell receptors in antiviral immunity.",
  "journal": "Immunity",
  "year": 2003,
  "authors": "Kjer-Nielsen L, Clements CS, Purcell AW, Brooks AG, Whisstock JC, Burrows SR, McCluskey J, Rossjohn J."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study examined an immunodominant \u03b1\u03b2 TCR recognizing an Epstein-Barr virus epitope presented on HLA class I, revealing how specific germline-encoded residues confer antigen specificity. Upon binding the pMHC complex, the TCR undergoes substantial conformational remodeling in its complementarity-determining regions, including disruption of canonical CDR1\u03b1 and CDR2\u03b1 structures to achieve optimal fit with the HLA-peptide surface. The findings establish a structural basis for TCR public clonotype selection in antiviral responses, showing that immunodominant TCR usage correlates with intrinsic structural properties that enable both high-affinity recognition and efficient conformational signaling through CD3 engagement, thereby linking TCR ligation mechanics to downstream intracellular activation pathways.",
